cluster_relations.rel_desc: Seabirds contribute to nutrient cycling via their nutrient deposition activities.

qualifiers.OtherQualifier: Mechanism: depositing marine-derived nutrients via guano

cluster_relations.rel_desc: Bird droppings redistribute nutrients and thus support nutrient cycling.

qualifiers.OtherQualifier: Mechanism: redistribution of nutrients via excreta

cluster_relations.rel_desc: Birds contribute essentially to the functioning and stability of ecosystems.

qualifiers.TemporalQualifier: around the world; general ongoing context
qualifiers.SpatialQualifier: ecosystems around the world; natural systems

args.canonical_rel_desc: Indicates that the subject provides a functional or causal contribution to the functioning, maintenance, or cycling processes of the object within an ecosystem context.
args.justification: All three relations describe a functional ecological contribution where the subject (seabirds, bird droppings, birds) causally supports or maintains an ecosystem-level process or state (nutrient cycling, ecosystems). They share the same direction and predicate meaning, so a single canonical predicate 'contributes_to' is appropriate.

Each relation captures that a biotic component or its byproducts contributes to an ecosystem process or state, which fits a common class of relations about contributions to ecosystem functioning (e.g., nutrient cycling, ecosystem stability). Grouping them under 'ecosystem_function_contribution_relation' reflects this shared ecological function framing.

In all instances, the subject is described as causally influencing or enabling the object process or state (e.g., seabirds and droppings cause/enable nutrient cycling, birds support ecosystem functioning), which is best captured by the broad semantic group CAUSALITY.
